v1.3.2

What's Changed

  • Simple MetricsSnapshot performance change by @​dhoard in prometheus/client_java#963
  • feat: add bearerToken builder to pushgateway exporter by @​FUSAKLA in prometheus/client_java#968
  • Fix UnknownDataPointSnapshot constructor by @​mimaison in prometheus/client_java#977

  • Fix PrometheusNaming.sanitizeMetricName() methods by @​mimaison in prometheus/client_java#975
  • additional improve MetricSnapshots.Builder performance by @​burov4j in prometheus/client_java#985

  • http server, add subject.doAs handler wrapper for exchange attribute … by @​gtully in prometheus/client_java#1089

  • use otel autoconfigure by @​zeitlinger in prometheus/client_java#1147
  • Add clear() method into PrometheusRegistry to unregister all collectors by @​zeitlinger in prometheus/client_java#1158

and stop are called on the critical path. We should have benchmarks for them to evaluate changes that may affect their performance. The benchmark is done differently than most other benchmarks because we want to isolate the time taken by starting a sample with a fixed number of existing samples and stopping a sample that hasn't been stopped. These both require specific states before the benchmarked code runs and that state will be altered by running the benchmark. If the state is not reset between benchmark invocations, we are measuring the time to start a new sample with increasingly more samples present, which we expect to take increasingly longer. That did not seem like the right approach. Likewise, the stop benchmark would result in stopping an already stopped sample if multiple invocations are made without resetting the state, which we expect to be substantially faster than stopping an unstopped sample. Suggestions are welcome on any better way to handle this.
